data.value: Visual Studio is a dots per inch (DPI) aware application, which means the display scales automatically. If an application states that it's not DPI-aware, the operating system scales the application as a bitmap. This behavior is also called DPI virtualization. The application still thinks that it's running at 100% scaling, or 96 dpi. This article discusses the limitations of Windows Forms Designer on HDPI monitors and how to run Visual Studio as a DPI-unaware process.Windows Forms Designer on HDPI monitors. The Windows Forms Designer in Visual Studio doesn't have scaling support. This causes display issues when you open some forms in the Windows Forms Designer on high dots per inch (HDPI) monitors.
